"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850836","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-05","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-03-05T09:48:52.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850836/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850836/answer","PQ 130062.pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850836/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-27","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the year-on-year changes to average weekly incomes in each constituency in each of the last 5 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","130062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850837","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Independent Case Examiner’s Office allocates complaints from women born in the 1950s affected by changes to State Pension age, to a dedicated team of investigation case managers, based on the date the complaint was accepted for examination. In the case of this group of complaints, investigations have to date been concluded within an average of 9.75 weeks of the investigation commencing, against a target of 20 weeks. We cannot provide reliable estimates of how long it will take to allocate and conclude investigations into those cases that are currently awaiting investigation.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-07T17:07:47.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850837/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850837/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 23 February 2018 to Question 128081, for what reason complaints from women born in the 1950s who are affected by changes in state pension age have not yet been allocated to an investigation case manager; what steps his Department is taking to ensure that those complaints are (a) allocated to an investigation case manager and (b) resolved in a timely manner; and how long the Department estimates it will take to (i) allocate, (ii) investigate and (iii) resolve those complaints.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","130063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850839","Department for Education","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Department publishes the amount spent by schools on supply teaching staff annually for:</p><p>Local authority maintained schools on the Department’s School and College Performance website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/school-performance-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/school-performance-tables</a> available for 2010-11 to 2016-17; and</p><p>Academies in the Department’s Statistical First Release ‘Income and expenditure in academies in England’ at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#academy-spending" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-local-authority-school-finance-data#academy-spending</a> available since 2011/12, when they were first collected in this format, up to 2015/16. Data for 2016/17 will published in the summer of 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working with Crown Commercial Service to develop a commercial framework for agency supply teachers to support schools with ensuring value for money when using agency staff. The framework is expected to be available for schools to use from September 2018.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-07T17:12:45.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850839/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850839/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-27","Supply Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much money was spent by (a) primary and (b) secondary schools in employing supply teachers in each of the last eight years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","130064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850840","Department for Education","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Department collects information on the number of higher level teaching assistants and cover supervisors employed in schools. However, no information is available on the amount of time these staff spend covering teaching absences.</p><p> </p><p>The full-time equivalent number of contracted staff whose role is defined as that of ‘higher level teaching assistant’ or of ‘cover supervisor’, employed by state funded schools in England, November 2010 to 2016 is provided in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>State Funded Schools</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Higher Level Teaching Assistant</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Cover Supervisor</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>11,040</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>..</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>12,150</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>7,490</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>13,380</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>8,010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>14,650</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>8,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>15,850</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>8,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>16,410</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>7,970</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>17,140</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>7,640</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: School Workforce Census<br> Figures are rounded to the nearest 10.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-07T16:26:44.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850840/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850840/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-27","Classroom Assistants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the use of (a) higher level teacher assistants and (b) cover supervisors to cover teaching absences.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","130065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850841","Department for Education","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Department does not register supply teacher agencies. However, the Crown Commercial Service (CCS) do have a list of agencies that currently hold the Recruitment and Employment Confederation (REC) Audited Education status. This is available on line and maintained by REC: <a href="https://www.rec.uk.com/business-support/audited/audited-members-directory" target="_blank">https://www.rec.uk.com/business-support/audited/audited-members-directory</a>.</p><p> </p><p>To support schools to achieve value for money when using supply agencies, we are working with CCS to develop a commercial framework for agency supply teachers. The framework will bring transparency to agency margins and require agencies to adhere to standard levels of practice, including the use of temp-to-perm fees. The framework is expected to be available for schools to use from September 2018.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-03-07T16:59:51.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850841/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850841/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-27","Supply Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will publish the names of all supply teacher agencies registered with his Department in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","130066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850842","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-07","<p>A significant amount of Ministry of Defence (MOD) business with Boeing is conducted through the Foreign Military Sales process. In addition, MOD central records have not yet been updated with our most recent contract awards, including any contracts with Boeing that might have been signed in the last two months. We have, however, signed one significant contract directly with Boeing since December 2017, which will be announced shortly.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-03-07T17:35:04.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850842/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850842/answer","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850842/answer/previousversion/44958","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850842/answer/previousversion/44958",,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-27","Boeing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many defence contracts his Department has awarded to Boeing since December 2017; and what the value of each of those contracts was.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","130067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850843","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>Mental health is a priority for this government. The Children and Young People’s Mental Health green paper outlines the government’s plans to set up a new national strategic partnership focused on improving the mental health of 16-25 year olds, encouraging more coordinated action, innovation and robust evaluation of mental health services. One recommendation in the green paper is for the partnership to provide a systematic strategy to improve what we know about student mental health by encouraging improvements in data linkage and analytics. Data is available from the Higher Education Statistical Agency on the number of higher education students who leave their course early for health reasons, but the data does not make it possible to distinguish mental health reasons specifically.</p><p> </p><p>The department is working closely with Universities UK on the programme of work on Mental Health in Higher Education, which has included work with the Institute for Public Policy Research to strengthen the evidence-base on mental health in higher education.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-03-06T10:27:16.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850843/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850843/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-27","Students: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the number of people who left their undergraduate degree course for mental health reasons in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","130068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850844","Home Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>While the information relating to sexual orientation and gender identification of foreign nationals who are granted refugee status is not routinely recorded, the Home Office remains committed to publishing information on the number of people claiming asylum on the basis of sexual orientation.</p><p>While the Department does not hold pre-July 2015 data in a reportable format and does not currently break down the data into the separate lesbian, gay, bisexual or transgender categories, experimental data on asylum claims lodged on the basis of sexual orientation, including the number of claimants who were granted asylum, between 1 July 2015 and 31 March 2017 is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/asylum-claims-on-the-basis-of-sexual-orientation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/asylum-claims-on-the-basis-of-sexual-orientation</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-06T19:10:01.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850844/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850844/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Asylum: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) lesbian, (b) gay, (c) bisexual and (d) transgender asylum seekers have been granted refugee status in the United Kingdom in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","130069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850846","Home Office","false","2018-03-05","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information in the format requested.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-05T19:22:06.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850846/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850846/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Musicians: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) musicians and (b) artists have been refused entry into the UK due to them being deemed not conducive to the public good.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","130070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850847","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-05","<p>The government is clear that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum and Living Wage (NMW) should receive it. Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not record statistics on complaints or investigations by reference to countries of the United Kingdom, Government regions, constituencies or counties.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) undertook a more detailed analysis of NMW enforcement by workplace regions over the 2015/16 and 2016/17 financial years for the government evidence to the Low Pay Commission (LPC). Information on NMW enforcement by workplace regions for earlier years is not readily available. The data included in the LPC regional analysis is limited to the arrears identified in HMRC investigations. Furthermore, the workplace regions in the analysis relate to the employer’s registered trading address, and not necessarily where the NMW arrears occurred or where the affected workers were based.</p><p> </p><p>Further information can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/561779/beis-16-37-national-minimum-wage-government-evidence-for-lpc-autumn-2016-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/561779/beis-16-37-national-minimum-wage-government-evidence-for-lpc-autumn-2016-report.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/630197/nmw-nlw-lpc-evidence-compliance-enforcement-2017.pdf</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-05T16:43:05.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850847/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850847/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-27","Minimum Wage: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the number of employers in Wales who paid national minimum wage arrears in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","130071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850848","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>As the Home Secretary told the house in her oral statement following publication of David Anderson's report, the Government is confident that David Anderson, MI5 and the Police asked the right questions and drew the right conclusions in their reviews following the attacks in London and Manchester between March and June 2017. Work on implementation is in progress and the Home Office is working closely with MI5, JTAC and the Police to ensure the recommendations are delivered.</p><p>In line with the recommendations, JTAC and MI5 accept they have a role to play in tackling this growing threat and are expanding their involvement in work to combat domestic terrorism. The Home Office acknowledges the benefit of updating the terms 'domestic extremism' and 'international counter terrorism’. We will publish our updated CONTEST strategy in the coming weeks.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","130073 ; 130313","2018-05-24T14:09:12.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850848/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850848/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the independent review by David Anderson QC entitled Attacks in London and Manchester, published in December 2017, whether the Joint Terrorism Analysis Centre is now responsible for producing national threat assessments of terrorist threats arising from domestic extremism.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","130072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850849","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>As the Home Secretary told the house in her oral statement following publication of David Anderson's report, the Government is confident that David Anderson, MI5 and the Police asked the right questions and drew the right conclusions in their reviews following the attacks in London and Manchester between March and June 2017. Work on implementation is in progress and the Home Office is working closely with MI5, JTAC and the Police to ensure the recommendations are delivered.</p><p>In line with the recommendations, JTAC and MI5 accept they have a role to play in tackling this growing threat and are expanding their involvement in work to combat domestic terrorism. The Home Office acknowledges the benefit of updating the terms 'domestic extremism' and 'international counter terrorism’. We will publish our updated CONTEST strategy in the coming weeks.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","130072 ; 130313","2018-05-24T14:09:12.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850849/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850849/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the independent review by David Anderson QC entitled Attacks in London and Manchester, published in December 2017, whether (a) MI5 (b) and the Joint Terrorism Analysis Centre will take on an increased role in domestic extremism work; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","130073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850851","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>All breaches of information are taken seriously and recorded by each individual department. The Civil Service Management Code (4.2.1) states ‘Departments and agencies must remind staff on appointment, retirement or resignation that they are bound by the provisions of the criminal law, including the Official Secrets Acts, which protect certain categories of official information, and by their duty of confidentiality owed to the Crown as their former employer’.</p><p>Where a law has been broken or potentially broken, it is reported to the police and they would take forward any investigation. Subsequent actions would be a matter for the police and the courts.</p><p>Other than in exceptional cases, when it is in the public interest, it has been the policy of successive governments not to comment on breaches of security.</p><p><strong><strong></strong><br></strong></p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-03-06T10:13:14.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850851/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850851/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-27","Civil Servants: Official Secrets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants have been (a) disciplined, (b) subject to criminal charges, and (c) dismissed for offences under the Official Secrets Act 1989 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","130074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850852","Home Office","false","2018-03-07","<p>The specific data requested is not published by the Home Office.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-07T15:57:41.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850852/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850852/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Passports: Lost Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports have been reported lost or mislaid by her Department and its agencies during immigration applications in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","130075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850853","Home Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>UK Visas and Immigration use various methods when returning valuable documents (including passports) to its customers, this is clearly set out to customers as part of the application process. Customers have the option to arrange recorded or special delivery should they wish. Or to apply using our premium routes which allows them to make an application without giving their documents up at all.</p><p>When we are informed of errors we work promptly to rectify them, including the loss of valuable documents. Customer feedback, including complaints, are taken into account to ensure we offer value for money; which includes improving the services we offer, the quality of the decisions we make and the provision of an excellent customer service.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-06T19:00:29.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850853/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850853/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Passports: Postal Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the policy of UK Immigration and Visas is on returning passports to immigration applicants by (a) recorded delivery, (b) first class post, (c) second class post and (d) other means.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","130076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850854","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-07","<p>Telford will be a Specialist Site location for HMRC that will include Digital Technology and Corporate Service functions. Over the past two years we have redeployed some of our IT specialists previously contracted to ASPIRE into HMRC Digital Technology Services. We are committed to invest in specialist skills and training for all of our people.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s Chief Digital Information Officer business area continues to recruit into Plaza (a nearby location), making opportunities available where possible to those HMRC staff in Abbey and Parkside and current workforce plans shows for this to continue. In addition Telford are also working to strengthen relationships with HMRC Birmingham as part of the West Midlands network, for example current initiatives include mental health networks.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-07T16:47:43.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850854/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850854/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-27","Revenue and Customs: Telford","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans HM Revenue and Customs has for the future of its staff working at Abbey House and Parkside Court in Telford.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","130077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850855","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-05","<p>The revenue raised by Dart Charge for financial years 2014-15, 2015-16 and 2016-17 can be found in the Dart Charge annual accounts which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=corporate-reports&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=highways-england&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=corporate-reports&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=highways-england&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date</a></p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-05T08:54:34.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850855/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850855/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-27","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what revenue has been raised by the Dart Charge in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","130078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850856","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-05","<p>​Whilst we have not made an assessment on this specific issue, we consider the Golan Heights to be Occupied Territory. We continue to call on Israel, as the occupying power, to uphold its obligations under international law. This includes abiding by UN Security Council Resolution 497 (1981) and the Fourth Geneva Convention.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-05T16:26:22.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850856/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850856/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-27","Golan Heights: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implications of Israel’s plans to hold local elections in the Golan Heights; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","130079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850858","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-07","<p>The government announced at Autumn Budget that it would extend the Save As You Earn (SAYE) contributions holiday from 6 to 12 months for those on maternity and parental leave from 6 April 2018. After receiving representations from the share plan industry, the government is delaying the implementation of this change until 1 September 2018 to allow for software changes and testing.</p><p> </p><p>The government will, from the same date, extend the SAYE contributions holiday to 12 months for all SAYE plans. This change will extend the benefit to all SAYE participants, including those with pre-existing contracts.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","130082 ; 130083","2018-03-07T16:30:07.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850858/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850858/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-27","Save as You Earn","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of deferring the upcoming increase in the contributions holiday for SAYE schemes from six to 12 months to allow more time for the share plan industry to undertake (a) system development and (b) regression testing.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","130080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850859","Home Office","false","2018-03-05","<p>I welcome the swift action taken by the National Police Chiefs’ Council and Association of Police and Crime Commissioners’ to manage the administration of Key Forensic Services (KFS), minimising the impact on the criminal justice system and protecting the evidence for live cases. With Home Office support, they reached an agreement with the Administrators to ensure that the business continues to operate so that evidence KFS holds continues to be properly and professionally managed in accordance with the standards set by the Forensic Science Regulator. There are no plans to reopen the Forensic Science Service.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-03-05T19:42:53.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850859/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850859/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Forensic Science","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps are being taken to protect forensic evidence following the collapse of Key Forensic Services; and if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of reopening the Forensic Science Service to ensure forensic work is not lost in the event of a contractor's closure.","false","Biography information for Kate Hollern","Blackburn","Kate Hollern","130081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850860","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-07","<p>The government announced at Autumn Budget that it would extend the Save As You Earn (SAYE) contributions holiday from 6 to 12 months for those on maternity and parental leave from 6 April 2018. After receiving representations from the share plan industry, the government is delaying the implementation of this change until 1 September 2018 to allow for software changes and testing.</p><p> </p><p>The government will, from the same date, extend the SAYE contributions holiday to 12 months for all SAYE plans. This change will extend the benefit to all SAYE participants, including those with pre-existing contracts.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","130080 ; 130083","2018-03-07T16:30:07.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850860/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850860/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-27","Save as You Earn: Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his planned increase to contributions holidays for SAYE schemes will apply to those (a) on maternity leave, (b) on shared parental leave, (c) on adoption leave and (d) who miss payment contributions.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","130082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850861","HM Treasury","false","2018-03-07","<p>The government announced at Autumn Budget that it would extend the Save As You Earn (SAYE) contributions holiday from 6 to 12 months for those on maternity and parental leave from 6 April 2018. After receiving representations from the share plan industry, the government is delaying the implementation of this change until 1 September 2018 to allow for software changes and testing.</p><p> </p><p>The government will, from the same date, extend the SAYE contributions holiday to 12 months for all SAYE plans. This change will extend the benefit to all SAYE participants, including those with pre-existing contracts.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","130080 ; 130082","2018-03-07T16:30:07.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850861/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850861/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-27","Save as You Earn","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the planned increase to the contributions holiday for SAYE schemes will apply to new SAYE contracts only or also cover pre-existing SAYE contracts.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","130083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850862","Home Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>Providing the information requested would require a manual check of individual records which could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p>All complaints to Immigration Enforcement are investigated. An apology will be offered where it is found that an error has been made.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-06T19:35:13.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850862/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850862/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) British citizens, (b) EEA nationals and (c) individuals with leave to remain or indefinite leave to remain have been wrongfully detained in immigration detention centres in each of the last five years; and will she make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","130084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850863","Department for Education","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Children’s Commissioner for England’s advisory board brings together individuals from across the children’s sector and wider civil society. Membership is by the formal invitation of the Children’s Commissioner following public advertisement and a recruitment exercise. The Children’s Commissioner selects members from applications received and they are invited on the basis of the following considerations:</p><p> </p><ul><li>a track record of excellence at a strategic policy and delivery level;</li><li>a track record of high strategic or operational performance to support services relevant to children young people and families;</li><li>proven knowledge and experience of policymaking and public affairs; and/or</li><li>knowledge of the role, remit, powers and duties of the Children’s Commissioner as defined in legislation.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The work of the advisory board is undertaken paying due regard to the seven principles of the Code of Conduct for those in Public Life. The terms of reference for the Advisory Board are publically available here: <a href="https://www.childrenscommissioner.gov.uk/report/advisory-board/" target="_blank">https://www.childrenscommissioner.gov.uk/report/<br> advisory-board/</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-07T16:28:51.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850863/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850863/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-27","Children's Commissioner for England: Advisory Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the selection process is for members of the Children's Commissioner's Advisory Board.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","130085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850864","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-07","<p>A managed information provision process began in July 2017 to inform all existing recipients of Support for Mortgage Interest (SMI) benefit of the new scheme. Claimants are given information about how the SMI loan will work, about alternatives to the loan and organisations that may offer further information and support. This is followed up by telephone calls to explain the information and answer any questions. A leaflet containing Frequently Asked Questions is issued to support this informed discussion. Where a claimant expresses an interest in taking up the offer of an SMI loan they will be sent a loan agreement and charge form to complete and return. They also receive detailed guidance on how to complete these documents.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-07T17:08:23.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850864/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850864/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department took to inform recipients of Support for Mortgage Interest of the changes from benefit to loan occurring on 5 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850866","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-06","<p>To date, the department has sent information to around 95% of SMI claimants at the address at which they are claiming SMI benefit. The remaining 5% of cases we have so far been unable to refer to Serco for a variety of reasons, such as the need to obtain a telephone number for the claimant.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-06T13:16:51.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850866/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850866/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether any recipients of Support for Mortgage Interest did not receive notice of the impending changes to the benefit scheduled for 5 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850867","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-07","<p>The Department determines that 6 weeks is a sufficient time period for claimants to make a decision whether to take up the offer of an SMI loan. The Department ask that the loan agreement and charge form are returned soon as reasonably possible to enable them to be processed efficiently. A reminder is sent out after six weeks if the documents have not been received. Claimants may change their mind whether to take or decline a loan at any time.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-07T17:08:31.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850867/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850867/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much time his Department deemed adequate to provide sufficient notice to those in receipt of Support for Mortgage Interest of the impending changes scheduled for 5 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850868","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-06","<p>To date, the department has sent information to around 95% of SMI claimants at the address at which they are claiming SMI benefit. In some cases we have so far been unable to contact claimants for a variety of reasons such as where we need to obtain a telephone number for the claimant. On current plans, the last contacts should be made by 26 March. The Loans for Mortgage Interest Regulations 2017 contain provision to extend payment of SMI benefit in these cases.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-06T13:16:53.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850868/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850868/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the latest date was by which recipients of Support for Mortgage Interest were made aware of the changes to the benefit scheduled for 5 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850869","Home Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Government is committed to protecting the public and providing the resources necessary for the police to do their work. The 2018/19 police funding settlement follows a period of engagement, during which I spoke to every police force in England and Wales about the demands they face and how these can best be managed.</p><p>The Government has ensured that, through the election of Police and Crime Commissioners, communities, including those in rural areas, have a strong voice in determining how police resources are allocated to tackle the crimes that matter most to them.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-03-06T19:21:50.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850869/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850869/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Crime: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment her Department has made of police forces' capacity to tackle rural crime; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850870","Home Office","true","2018-03-05","<p><del class="ministerial">I welcome the swift action taken by the National Police Chiefs’ Council and Association of Police and Crime Commissioners’ to manage the administration of Key Forensic Services (KFS), minimising the impact on the criminal justice system and protecting the evidence for live cases. With Home Office support, they reached an agreement with the Administrators to ensure that the business continues to operate so that evidence KFS holds continues to be properly and professionally managed in accordance with the standards set by the Forensic Science Regulator.There are no plans to reopen the Forensic Science Service.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Government has not undertaken an assessment of the effect of rural crime on residents and businesses in Barnsley East. The independent Crime Survey for England and Wales continues to show that, for those crimes covered by the Survey, people in rural areas are less likely to be the victims of crime than those in urban areas. The 2015 Commercial Victimisation Survey also showed that 24 per cent of agriculture, forestry and fishing premises in England and Wales, had experienced at least one incident of crime (excluding online crime) which represented a statistically significant fall of six percentage points compared with the 2013 Survey.</ins></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-03-05T19:32:12.71Z","2018-03-05T20:54:45.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850870/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850870/answer","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850870/answer/previousversion/44974","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850870/answer/previousversion/44974",,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Crime: Barnsley East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment her Department has made on the effects of rural crime on (a) residents and (b) business in Barnsley East constituency.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850871","Home Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>We do not publish this specific data, however information on the average time for a decision to be taken on an Indefinite Leave to Remain application, by geographical area, is not held by the Home Office.</p><p>The current maximum waiting time for a straightforward application for indefinite leave to remain under the settlement route is six months, there are currently no plans to change this.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","130093","2018-03-06T19:17:03.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850871/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850871/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken was for a decision on settlement or indefinite leave to remain applications from submission to response in (a) Barnsley and (b) England in each of the last 3 years.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850873","Home Office","false","2018-03-06","<p>We do not publish this specific data, however information on the average time for a decision to be taken on an Indefinite Leave to Remain application, by geographical area, is not held by the Home Office.</p><p>The current maximum waiting time for a straightforward application for indefinite leave to remain under the settlement route is six months, there are currently no plans to change this.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","130092","2018-03-06T19:17:03.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850873/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850873/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-27","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the target time is for her Department to reach a decision on indefinite leave to remain applications; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850874","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-07","<p><strong> </strong><strong></strong>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","130095","2018-03-07T11:18:26.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850874/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850874/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-27","Universal Credit: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of universal credit recipients in receipt of disability benefit with non-dependents living at their home receiving housing cost contribution deductions for non-dependents.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","130094"
