"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850170","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Department published National Health Service patient, visitor and staff car parking principles on 23 August 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The principles state that concessions, including free or reduced charges or caps, should be available for disabled people, including people with temporary disabilities as well as Blue Badge holders. As in other settings, the access the Blue Badge Scheme provides does not preclude the making of some level of charge in some cases.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS itself is responsible for ensuring that charges are fairly applied. Patients, visitors and staff who have problems with car parking should therefore contact the NHS organisation which runs the car park.</p><p> </p><p>On concessions, the principles are as follows;</p><p>Concessions including free or reduced charges or caps should be available for the following groups:</p><p>- disabled people;</p><p>- frequent outpatient attenders;</p><p>- visitors with relatives who are gravely ill, or carers of such people;</p><p>- visitors to relatives who have an extended stay in hospital, or carers of such people;</p><p>- carers of people in the above groups where appropriate; and</p><p>- staff working shifts that mean public transport cannot be used.</p><p> </p><p>NHS car parking data including the number of hospitals charging for disabled parking is collected annually through Estates Return Information Collection (ERIC). All ERIC data is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/ERIC.asp" target="_blank">http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/ERIC.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest available data for 2016-17 sets out that 132 hospitals sites in England charge for disabled parking.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","129739","2018-03-06T16:03:47.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850170/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850170/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what his policy is on hospitals charging blue badge holders for parking.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850171","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Department published National Health Service patient, visitor and staff car parking principles on 23 August 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The principles state that concessions, including free or reduced charges or caps, should be available for disabled people, including people with temporary disabilities as well as Blue Badge holders. As in other settings, the access the Blue Badge Scheme provides does not preclude the making of some level of charge in some cases.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS itself is responsible for ensuring that charges are fairly applied. Patients, visitors and staff who have problems with car parking should therefore contact the NHS organisation which runs the car park.</p><p> </p><p>On concessions, the principles are as follows;</p><p>Concessions including free or reduced charges or caps should be available for the following groups:</p><p>- disabled people;</p><p>- frequent outpatient attenders;</p><p>- visitors with relatives who are gravely ill, or carers of such people;</p><p>- visitors to relatives who have an extended stay in hospital, or carers of such people;</p><p>- carers of people in the above groups where appropriate; and</p><p>- staff working shifts that mean public transport cannot be used.</p><p> </p><p>NHS car parking data including the number of hospitals charging for disabled parking is collected annually through Estates Return Information Collection (ERIC). All ERIC data is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/ERIC.asp" target="_blank">http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/ERIC.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>The latest available data for 2016-17 sets out that 132 hospitals sites in England charge for disabled parking.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","129738","2018-03-06T16:03:47.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850171/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850171/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Hospitals: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the number of hospitals charging blue badge holders for parking.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850172","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Department’s non-departmental public bodies (NDPBs) have provided the attached information.</p><p> </p><p>NDPBs are able to procure staff from the Crown Commercial Services (CCS) Non-Medical Non Clinical framework for permanent and temporary workers and the CCS Contingent Labour One framework for temporary workers.</p><p> </p><p>The two frameworks are not mandated for NDPBs to use, and are able to use alternative routes to procure staff.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-03-06T13:50:00.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850172/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850172/answer","NDPBs - recruitment agencies table 28th Feb.docx","PQ129740 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850172/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Department of Health and Social Care: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what external recruitment agencies are used by his Department’s non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850173","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-05","<p>The available information on Jobseeker’s Allowance, Employment and Support Allowance, Income Support and Universal Credit sanction decisions by parliamentary constituency is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-05T16:10:20.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850173/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850173/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-26","Social Security Benefits: Ellesmere Port and Neston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many sanctions have been made against claimants in Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency in each of the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850174","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-06","<p>The Independent Case Examiner’s Office currently has 19 complaints from the Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency awaiting allocation to an investigation case manager.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-06T13:16:20.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850174/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850174/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-26","Social Security Benefits: Ellesmere Port and Neston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints from Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency are awaiting allocation to an investigation case manager at the Independent Case Examiner’s Office.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850175","Home Office","false","2018-03-15","<p>The Government sympathises deeply with the situation faced by Alfie Dingley and his family. The Policing and Fire Minister met Alfie Dingley’s family on 26 February. Both the Home Secretary and Mr. Hurd want to explore every option within the current regulatory framework.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-03-15T19:23:40.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850175/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850175/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-26","Cannabis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has plans to introduce the use of all forms of medicinal cannabis.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","129743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850176","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-06","<p>There is a rolling 3 year deadline for local authorities to use the receipts from additional Right to Buy sales for new affordable housing and so far, they have delivered within sales profile. However, the Government is keen to understand if more can be done to encourage faster delivery of Right to Buy replacements. We have been engaging with local authorities to get their views, which will be fed into our assessment.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-03-06T12:49:57.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850176/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850176/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-26","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Government’s policies on the replacement of homes sold under the right to buy.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850177","Department for Education","false","2018-03-06","<p>The proportion of pupils eligible for and claiming free school meals is published at the annual ‘Schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical release,</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not summarised by parliamentary constituency, but data for each school is available in the Underlying data: SFR28/2017 of the annual ‘Schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical release, contained in file ‘SFR28_2017_Schools_Pupils_UD’. The figures can be filtered by school phase, school type and parliamentary constituency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information for earlier years (from 2010 onwards) can be found at</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-and-pupil-numbers</a>.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-06T09:38:53.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850177/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850177/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-26","Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many pupils were entitled to free school meals in (a) Ellesmere Port and Neston constituency and (b) England in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850178","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-05","<p>The Government has no plans to bring forward legislative proposals to ban tolls on river crossings. It is Government policy that those who benefit from the significant improvements that estuarial crossings bring should help to pay for them. Successive Governments have taken the view that tolls are justified when private finance enables key road infrastructure such as significant river crossings to proceed and to be maintained.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-05T08:45:22.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850178/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850178/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-26","Bridges: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to ban tolls on river crossings.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850179","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-05","<p>Detailed revenue financing data from all local authorities in England are published each year on the Department's website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p><p> </p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-03-05T09:06:43.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850179/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850179/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-26","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the local government budget came from council tax in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","129747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850180","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-05","<p>Nexus are responsible for the management of the procurement, delivery and rollout of the new fleet of trains. Nexus provide the Department for Transport with regular updates on this procurement work as part of its regular reporting.</p><p> </p><p>The Periodic Indicative Notice (PIN) for the procurement of the new fleet by Nexus was published on 25 January 2018.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-05T08:31:39.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850180/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850180/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-26","Tyne and Wear Metro: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent progress he has made on the procurement, delivery and rollout of the new fleet of trains for the Tyne and Wear Metro.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","129748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850181","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-01","<p>The payment of state pensions to UK nationals has not been outsourced.</p><p> </p><p>Benefit and pension payments are dispersed to overseas customers on their due date in accordance with clearance times stipulated by each countries international clearing house. These can fluctuate between 2 and 11 days, depending on the countries processing regulations.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-03-01T14:17:20.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850181/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850181/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-26","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the timeliness of state pension payments to UK nationals living abroad whose payments have been outsourced to an American Bank.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","129749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850182","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Payment of state pensions to UK nationals has not been outsourced.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Work and Pensions continues to make assessments for all customer benefits. When issuing benefits and pensions to customers overseas, the Department has to use a sponsor bank to facilitate the payments. The Department’s current banking provider for overseas payments is Citibank N.A (London Branch). The Bulk Foreign Exchange Services contract is contracted by HM Revenue &amp; Customs through the office of Government Banking on behalf of the Department for Work and Pensions. Benefit and pension payments to overseas countries are forwarded by Citibank to the appropriate country’s clearing service which then disperses them directly to the customer’s chosen bank.</p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-03-01T14:11:56.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850182/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850182/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-26","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department has outsourced the payment of state pensions for UK nationals who live abroad to a bank based in the United States.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","129750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850183","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-06","<p>Decisions on configuration are best taken by the local National Health Service, who can best assess how to meet the needs of people in their area.</p><p> </p><p>For any significant system reconfiguration, we expect all local parts of the system to be talking to the public and stakeholders regularly — it is vital that people can shape the future of their local services.</p><p> </p><p>All significant service change is subject to a full public consultation and proposals must meet the government’s four reconfiguration tests. These are support from clinical commissioners, clarity on the clinical evidence base, robust patient and public engagement and support for patient choice. There is additional NHS England guidance (fifth test) which means that proposed service reconfigurations should be tested for their impact on overall bed numbers in the area.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities play a key role in ensuring the democratic accountability of local health services, through their statutory oversight and scrutiny committees. Should such a committee remain unsatisfied with the handling of a proposed service change, one of their options is to ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care to consider undertaking his own review.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","129927","2018-03-06T14:05:53.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850183/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850183/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","South Tyneside Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will undertake a review of the decision made by Sunderland and South Tyneside clinical commissioning groups to downgrade South Tyneside District Hospital.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","129751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850184","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-05","<p>The information requested is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Section</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A19 Seaton Burn to Tyne Tunnel</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fatal</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Serious</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slight</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A19 Tyne Tunnel to A181</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fatal</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Serious</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slight</p></td><td><p>94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>102</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A19: A181 to Tees Crossing</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fatal</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Serious</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slight</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>A19: Tees Crossing down to A168</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fatal</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Serious</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slight</p></td><td><p>48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>56</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-05T08:28:12.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850184/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850184/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-26","A19: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the number of collisions on the A19 road in the North East.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","129752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850185","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-06","<p>Sport England, government's arms length body, is spending over a billion pounds over the next four years to support grassroots sport. The Football Foundation is an organisation investing £60m each year into improving the country's grassroots football and sports infrastructure with money provided by its funding partners: the Premier League, The FA and the Government (via Sport England)</p><p> </p><p>Total grassroots football investment (Sport England and Football Foundation) for the North East is over £22m since 2010 and a full breakdown of figures for other grassroots sports funded by Sport England are available on their website, <a href="http://www.sportengland.org" target="_blank">www.sportengland.org</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Responsibility for grassroots sport is devolved and each country has a Home Nation Sports Council, sportscotland, Sport Wales and Sport Northern Ireland in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland respectively.</p><p> </p><p>UK Sport, ​which receives funding from the UK government and the National Lottery, prepares athletes for Olympic and Paralympic Games across the UK, and is investing up to £345m to fund at least 38 sports across the current 4-year Tokyo 2020 Summer Olympic and Paralympic funding cycle. UK Sport has also invested over £32m into Winter Olympic and Paralympic sports in the current PyeongChang 2018 funding cycle.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-06T13:31:10.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850185/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850185/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-02-26","Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to support (a) grassroots football and (b) other sports in (i) Jarrow constituency, (ii) South Tyneside, (iii) the North East and (iv) the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","129753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850186","Wales Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Wales Office does not have any non-departmental public bodies.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-03-01T17:27:30.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850186/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850186/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-02-26","Wales Office: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, which external recruitment agencies are used by his Department's non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","129754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850187","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>My Department has four non-departmental public bodies – the Independent Reporting Commission; the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission; the Parades Commission for Northern Ireland; and the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland. As these bodies operate independently of Government, the hon Member may wish to write to the Commissions directly on these matters – contact details are set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>ALB</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Status</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contact Details</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Independent Reporting Commission</p></td><td><p>Executive NDPB</p></td><td><p>enquiries@IRCommission.org</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission</p></td><td><p>Executive NDPB</p></td><td><p>information@nihrc.org</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parades Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>Executive NDPB</p></td><td><p>info@paradescommission.org</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>Advisory NDPB</p></td><td><p>bcni@belfast.org.uk</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-03-01T11:30:36.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850187/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850187/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-02-26","Northern Ireland Office: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, which external recruitment agencies are used by her Department's non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","129755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850189","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The recommendations from the National Emergency Pressures Panel to help trusts manage sustained pressures during winter were announced on 2 January 2018 and remained in place until 31 January 2018. This included temporarily suspending sanctions for mixed sex accommodation breaches.</p><p> </p><p>Providers of National Health Service-funded healthcare reported 1,908 breaches of the mixed sex accommodation guidance in relation to NHS patients in sleeping accommodation in England during January 2018.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-01T15:27:09.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850189/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850189/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-26","Hospital Wards: Gender","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, for how many days of winter 2017-18 NHS Improvement suspended penalties for mixed sex accommodation breaches; how many breaches took place during this time; and whether penalties have been restored.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","129757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850190","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-01","<p>We are carefully considering the issues around society lotteries raised by the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee and will continue to take advice from the Gambling Commission as we consider policy options. The Government’s response to the Committee’ advised that it intended to explore all their recommendations further. and can be found here: https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmselect/cmcumeds/415/415.pdf</p><p> </p><p>We hope to conclude considerations and provide an update in due course.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-03-01T13:42:55.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850190/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850190/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-02-26","Lotteries: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2018 to Question 126140, on Lotteries: Regulation, what the nature of the advice requested by his Department from the Gambling Commission was; what specific policy options his Department are considering; and when his Department plans to come to a conclusion on this issue.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","129758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850191","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-01","<p>Serco do not undertake SMI loan processing being contracted solely to provide information to claimants in the form of letters, leaflets and telephone ‘Informed Discussions’. These Informed Discussions will continue to be offered to new applicants who are eligible for the SMI loan.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-01T14:33:12.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850191/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/850191/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-26","Mortgages: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what date her Department estimates that the processing of SMI replacement loans claims by Serco will be completed.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","129759"
